arty leaders, and as representatives of the Crown at all levels of government across Canada. Prospects for gender parity in political office are assessed in each jurisdiction and institution. Explanations are re-examined and analyzed using data from across the country. The representation of women in elected and appointed offices is an important indicator of both gender equality and the overall health of democratic governance. By this measure Canada continues to fall short.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomen legislatorszCanada. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Women in Politics.2bisacsh1 aArscott, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArscott, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBashevkin, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerdahl, Loleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBittner, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarbert, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossley, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEveritt, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodyear-Grant, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMullen, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMévellec, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Neill, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPraud, Jocelyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaney, Tracey, econtributor.